62
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:46,860
But the need to fill the void

63
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:49,379
in its place remains. And while

64
00:02:46,860 --> 00:02:52,500
another of Dostoevsky's characters

65
00:02:49,379 --> 00:02:55,019
in "Demons" says, "If there is no God,

66
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:58,860
then what kind of captain am I after that?"

67
00:02:55,019 --> 00:02:59,940
Kirillov says, "If there is no God,

68
00:02:58,860 --> 00:03:03,120
then I can take His place."

69
00:02:59,940 --> 00:03:06,500
Remember, Grebenshchikov sang: "You feel

70
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:10,620
the draft because that place is vacant."

71
00:03:06,500 --> 00:03:13,200
Kirillov senses that very draft, and

72
00:03:10,620 --> 00:03:15,659
he formulates a terrifying, mad idea,

73
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:19,019
which he then falls in love with: "If a person,"

74
00:03:15,659 --> 00:03:21,900
he says, "decides to assert his will

75
00:03:19,019 --> 00:03:23,760
and simply ends his life, not out of anger,

76
00:03:21,900 --> 00:03:27,540
fear, or malice, but precisely because

77
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:30,060
he has the right, then," Kirillov argues,

78
00:03:27,540 --> 00:03:32,459
"with this step, he will regenerate

79
00:03:30,060 --> 00:03:34,379
all of humanity and himself become

80
00:03:32,459 --> 00:03:36,900
man's God."

79
00:03:30,060 --> 00:03:34,379
As all humanity steps forward — one itself will become

80
00:03:32,459 --> 00:03:36,900
God to man

81
00:03:34,379 --> 00:03:40,500
But they tell him, there have already been millions of suicides

82
00:03:36,900 --> 00:03:43,400
yet still no

83
00:03:40,500 --> 00:03:47,040
fear, and not for that reason, Kirillov objects

84
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:49,680
and his mad approach surprisingly

85
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:52,799
resembles an episode from 'Don Quixote'.

86
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:54,900
Remember, when daring and far, says Sancho Panza,

87
00:03:52,799 --> 00:03:57,420
who plans to emulate the glorious knights

88
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:58,879
of the past and go mad.

89
00:03:57,420 --> 00:04:02,220
The pragmatic Sancho then asks:

90
00:03:58,879 --> 00:04:04,019
'And do you have a reason to go mad,

91
00:04:02,220 --> 00:04:07,980
señor?'. What's the reason?

92
00:04:04,019 --> 00:04:10,980
That’s the crux of it, replies Don Quixote.

93
00:04:07,980 --> 00:04:12,900
That’s the very peculiarity

94
00:04:10,980 --> 00:04:15,599
of my intended enterprise.

95
00:04:12,900 --> 00:04:18,000
Whoever among the knight-errants

96
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:20,519
went mad for some reason

97
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,160
should ask neither for a

98
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:26,340
reward nor gratitude.

96
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:20,519
The knight, for some reason, went mad.

97
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,160
He does not seek rewards or gratitude:

98
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:26,340
the whole point is to

99
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:29,460
go mad without any reason.

100
00:04:26,340 --> 00:04:31,979
And, as we will soon see,

101
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:33,300
these echoes in the words of Kirillov

102
00:04:31,979 --> 00:04:36,180
and Quixote are far from accidental.

